    <h1 class="display-4">Flying Airplanes is Fun!</h1>
    <img src="~/img/img1.jpg" />
    <img src="~/img/img2.jpg" />

    <p>
        Flying planes is one of those experiences that never really gets old for me. There’s something about sitting in the cockpit, running through the checklist, and feeling the engine come alive that always brings a quiet excitement. It’s a mix of focus and freedom—every control input matters, every gauge has a story to tell, and yet the moment the wheels leave the ground, the world feels wide open. Up there, distractions fall away and it’s just me, the aircraft, and the sky.

        <br /><br />I like how flying demands both discipline and intuition. Planning the route, checking the weather, calculating performance—it all requires careful thought before takeoff. But once airborne, there’s a rhythm to it. Adjusting trim, scanning instruments, watching the horizon, and feeling the subtle movements of the air through the controls becomes almost second nature. It’s a skill that rewards patience and attention, and I find a lot of satisfaction in that balance.

        <br /><br />There’s also a perspective you only get from above. Familiar places look completely different from the air, like a map coming to life. Roads become lines, neighborhoods turn into patterns, and landscapes stretch out in ways you never notice from the ground. It gives me a sense of calm and appreciation for how everything fits together, and it reminds me why I love being up there in the first place.

        <br /><br />Most of all, flying makes me feel capable and present. It’s an activity where I’m fully engaged, aware of my surroundings, and responsible for every decision. That sense of responsibility, paired with the freedom of being in the sky, is what keeps drawing me back to the cockpit.
    </p>
